  <abstract displayLabel="Description">Smith recalls African American-owned businesses in South Baton Rouge including restaurants, barber shops, grocery stores, beauty shops, drug stores, etc. He explains how African American-owned businesses could not compete with white businesses following integration and how many were forced to close. He describes a typical day in the neighborhood and how the African American church is a success story among minority-owned businesses.</abstract>
  <abstract displayLabel="Link to Abstract">http://www.lib.lsu.edu/sites/all/files/oralhistory/abstracts/mckinley/2_businesses/Smith_Charles_T1041.pdf</abstract>
  <note type="content" displayLabel="Note">This collection includes materials accessioned as Mss. 4700.0714. A digital version of the transcript (pdf) exists for duplication purposes. A digital version of the audio recording (mp3) exists for duplication purposes and public access in the Special Collections Reading Room. Interview conducted by Michael Goods and Rudolph Henry.</note>
  <note type="biographical/historical" displayLabel="Biographical Note">Reverend Charles T. Smith graduated from McKinley High School in 1948. He attended Southern University and the New Orleans Baptist Theological Seminary and received his Doctor of Divinity from Union Baptist Theological Seminary. He serves as the pastor of Shiloh Missionary Baptist Church in Baton Rouge.</note>
